WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.285 --> 00:00:08.187
<i>Previously on</i>
Criminal Minds: Evolution...

2
00:00:08.287 --> 00:00:10.121
- (gasps)
- Everything okay?

3
00:00:10.222 --> 00:00:12.324
Henry got into San Diego.

4
00:00:12.457 --> 00:00:13.692
(cheering)

5
00:00:13.792 --> 00:00:15.494
With whom do we have
the pleasure of speaking?

6
00:00:15.594 --> 00:00:17.196
<i>LANCE (over phone):
Call me God.</i>

7
00:00:17.296 --> 00:00:20.699
I recognize that voice.
It's Lance Kingston.

8
00:00:20.799 --> 00:00:22.601
<i>PRENTISS:
But he can't be our guy.</i>

9
00:00:22.701 --> 00:00:23.702
<i>LEWIS:
He's his hostage.</i>

10
00:00:23.802 --> 00:00:25.304
<i>He's been branded.</i>

11
00:00:25.404 --> 00:00:27.306
Until we have the confidence

12
00:00:27.439 --> 00:00:28.940
that you're willing
to work with us.

13
00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:30.674
we have to limit your access
to the outside world.

14
00:00:30.675 --> 00:00:32.311
How much more limited
can my access possibly be?

15
00:00:32.411 --> 00:00:35.447
Your visitors are restricted
to the family members

16
00:00:35.547 --> 00:00:37.916
you've already agreed
to talk to. and that's it.

17
00:00:38.016 --> 00:00:39.418
JOSHUA RYAN:
Mr. Voit.

18
00:00:39.518 --> 00:00:40.685
(door closes)

19
00:00:40.819 --> 00:00:42.321
My name is Joshua Ryan.

20
00:00:42.421 --> 00:00:44.823
<i>Deena Ryan was my cousin.</i>

21
00:00:44.923 --> 00:00:47.191
ROSSI:
I don't see you yelling for the warden

22
00:00:47.192 --> 00:00:52.663
to let you call the BAU and
tell them you found your Fan.

23
00:00:52.664 --> 00:00:56.034
You do think I'm pathetic.

24
00:00:56.134 --> 00:00:58.001
Now. what did you want
to show me?

25
00:00:58.002 --> 00:01:00.372
(sighs)

26
00:01:03.041 --> 00:01:04.343
I'll fucking kill you.

27
00:01:04.443 --> 00:01:05.877
You're not gonna
fucking kill me.

28
00:01:06.010 --> 00:01:07.412
You're not even gonna
have me arrested

29
00:01:07.512 --> 00:01:10.315
'cause you know I wouldn't
have walked in here

30
00:01:10.415 --> 00:01:12.884
if I didn't have
a plan for this.

31
00:01:15.654 --> 00:01:17.789
Now who's pathetic?

32
00:01:21.293 --> 00:01:23.428
♪ ♪

33
00:01:25.897 --> 00:01:28.066
(birds chirping)

34
00:01:30.235 --> 00:01:32.404
(clock ticking)

35
00:01:34.406 --> 00:01:35.707
ARTURO:
Geez. I mean. with the add-ons.

36
00:01:35.807 --> 00:01:37.041
it's like we're buying
a car here.

37
00:01:37.141 --> 00:01:39.209
SARITA:
Arturo. please.

38
00:01:39.210 --> 00:01:40.412
Stop.

39
00:01:40.545 --> 00:01:42.213
Seriously. at this rate.

40
00:01:42.347 --> 00:01:45.416
we're not gonna get out of here
for less than 12.000 bucks.

41
00:01:45.417 --> 00:01:47.286
- (Sarita sighs)
- You got any cremation options?

42
00:01:47.386 --> 00:01:49.454
No. we just can't.

43
00:01:49.554 --> 00:01:51.589
That's what we're gonna do.

44
00:01:51.590 --> 00:01:54.091
Yes. but I promised Papé

45
00:01:54.092 --> 00:01:55.694
that I'd give him
a proper burial.

46
00:01:55.794 --> 00:01:57.429
ARTURO:
He wouldn't want us to take out

47
00:01:57.529 --> 00:02:00.230
- a second mortgage to do it.
- (chuckles softly)

48
00:02:00.231 --> 00:02:02.434
Please forgive my husband.

49
00:02:02.534 --> 00:02:04.735
I completely understand.

50
00:02:04.736 --> 00:02:07.339
And if I could. I would try
to offer you a better deal.

51
00:02:07.439 --> 00:02:11.109
but. truthfully.
all of our costs have risen.

52
00:02:11.242 --> 00:02:13.578
No. we do understand.

53
00:02:13.678 --> 00:02:14.846
We do.

54
00:02:14.946 --> 00:02:17.949
And Uncle Victor's funeral
was just...

55
00:02:18.049 --> 00:02:20.618
- so lovely.
- Thank you.

56
00:02:20.619 --> 00:02:23.688
Your mother.
she did such wonderful work.

57
00:02:23.788 --> 00:02:25.957
How is she?

58
00:02:26.958 --> 00:02:29.428
Uh. she's passed.

59
00:02:29.561 --> 00:02:30.995
Six months ago.

60
00:02:31.095 --> 00:02:32.797
Oh. I'm so sorry.

61
00:02:32.931 --> 00:02:34.265
Thank you.

62
00:02:34.366 --> 00:02:36.134
SARITA:
Our condolences.

63
00:02:36.267 --> 00:02:37.769
Sweetheart.

64
00:02:37.902 --> 00:02:40.271
Can we just take a little more
time to think about all this?

65
00:02:40.372 --> 00:02:41.640
Uh...

66
00:02:41.773 --> 00:02:43.273
May we call you later?

67
00:02:43.274 --> 00:02:46.545
Of course. And while we don't
do cremation on site.

68
00:02:46.645 --> 00:02:48.780
I can arrange everything.

69
00:02:48.880 --> 00:02:50.449
And you might like
to take a look

70
00:02:50.549 --> 00:02:52.784
at some of these beautiful urns.

71
00:02:55.153 --> 00:02:56.954
- Oh. cool. Thanks.
- Uh. no. we...

72
00:02:56.955 --> 00:02:59.122
we won't be needing that.
(chuckles)

73
00:02:59.123 --> 00:03:02.226
Uh. we'll be in touch.
(sniffles)

74
00:03:06.498 --> 00:03:08.667
(door opens)

75
00:03:14.839 --> 00:03:17.742
- (footsteps)
- (sighing)

76
00:03:19.978 --> 00:03:23.181
Good afternoon. Mrs. Enright.

77
00:03:25.950 --> 00:03:28.853
The psoriasis on your neck
clear up?

78
00:03:30.422 --> 00:03:31.989
Good.

79
00:03:31.990 --> 00:03:34.225
(sighs)

80
00:03:35.293 --> 00:03:37.462
(phone beeps. line rings)

81
00:03:37.562 --> 00:03:40.131
Good afternoon. This is Marvin.

82
00:03:40.965 --> 00:03:43.768
Yes. from Bancroft Mortuary.

83
00:03:44.736 --> 00:03:49.173
I just wanted to let you know
that Mrs. Enright is ready.

84
00:03:51.109 --> 00:03:53.211
Yes.

85
00:03:53.311 --> 00:03:55.246
8:00 a.m. on Thursday
is perfect.

86
00:03:55.346 --> 00:03:58.383
You have a wonderful
rest of your day.

87
00:03:59.217 --> 00:04:00.685
(phone beeps)

88
00:04:00.785 --> 00:04:02.954
♪ ♪

89
00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:10.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

90
00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:26.878
<i>NARRATOR (on audiobook):</i>
Chapters of Grief. <i>chapter four.</i>

91
00:04:26.978 --> 00:04:29.781
<i>"Grieving Deliberately."</i>

92
00:04:31.082 --> 00:04:35.186
<i>Too often.
we try to rush our grief.</i>

93
00:04:35.286 --> 00:04:38.056
<i>We simply want
to push through it</i>

94
00:04:38.156 --> 00:04:41.526
<i>so that we may move on
with our everyday lives.</i>

95
00:04:41.626 --> 00:04:46.465
<i>But when it's someone
close to you who passes.</i>

96
00:04:46.565 --> 00:04:49.734
<i>it leaves a wound.</i>

97
00:04:49.834 --> 00:04:53.104
<i>Just like any other
bodily injury.</i>

98
00:04:53.237 --> 00:04:57.809
<i>it requires care and patience.</i>

99
00:04:57.909 --> 00:05:00.311
<i>If you break your ankle
one day.</i>

100
00:05:00.411 --> 00:05:02.613
<i>you're not going to wake up
the next morning</i>

101
00:05:02.614 --> 00:05:05.684
<i>and run a marathon.</i>

102
00:05:05.784 --> 00:05:09.921
<i>So. as you process your grief.</i>

103
00:05:10.021 --> 00:05:12.122
<i>you must remind yourself</i>

104
00:05:12.123 --> 00:05:15.960
<i>that wounds take time to heal</i>

105
00:05:16.094 --> 00:05:19.197
<i>and accept that you are human.</i>

106
00:05:20.364 --> 00:05:22.033
<i>We eat.</i>

107
00:05:22.133 --> 00:05:24.268
<i>We sleep.</i>

108
00:05:25.103 --> 00:05:26.838
<i>We bleed.</i>

109
00:05:27.706 --> 00:05:30.208
<i>We grieve.</i>

110
00:05:30.308 --> 00:05:31.910
<i>All you can do is just</i>

111
00:05:32.010 --> 00:05:35.113
<i>put one foot
in front of the other.</i>

112
00:05:35.213 --> 00:05:38.449
<i>and when you open your eyes
each morning.</i>

113
00:05:38.583 --> 00:05:43.287
<i>accept every waking minute
for what it is:</i>

114
00:05:43.387 --> 00:05:47.726
<i>an essential part
of your grieving journey.</i>

115
00:05:48.627 --> 00:05:50.194
(exhales)

116
00:05:51.395 --> 00:05:53.798
(weak. shallow breathing)

117
00:05:53.932 --> 00:05:55.500
Stop.

118
00:05:55.634 --> 00:05:58.637
- MARVIN: It's okay.
- Stop.

119
00:05:58.770 --> 00:06:00.338
- MARVIN: Don't worry.
- (grunts)

120
00:06:00.438 --> 00:06:03.642
- You're doing great.
- (grunts weakly. whimpers)

121
00:06:03.775 --> 00:06:05.810
Shh.

122
00:06:05.910 --> 00:06:07.812
<i>NARRATOR (on audiobook):
Like a deep. running river</i>

123
00:06:07.946 --> 00:06:10.314
<i>churning and flowing.</i>

124
00:06:10.414 --> 00:06:15.520
<i>grief tends to resolve itself
on its own terms.</i>

125
00:06:15.620 --> 00:06:18.022
<i>You can choose to fight it...</i>

126
00:06:18.156 --> 00:06:20.024
(whirring. burbling)

127
00:06:20.158 --> 00:06:23.327
<i>...resist its chaotic nature.</i>

128
00:06:23.461 --> 00:06:26.329
<i>or choose to embrace it.</i>

129
00:06:26.330 --> 00:06:29.332
<i>And no matter how powerless
you may feel...</i>

130
00:06:29.333 --> 00:06:30.969
(gasping breaths)

131
00:06:31.069 --> 00:06:33.003
<i>...always remember</i>

132
00:06:33.004 --> 00:06:38.843
<i>that you are someone
who deserves love and respect.</i>

133
00:06:39.711 --> 00:06:43.848
<i>And that you are
the only one who decides</i>

134
00:06:43.982 --> 00:06:48.352
<i>whether or not
you will have a good day.</i>

135
00:06:49.788 --> 00:06:51.956
♪ ♪

136
00:07:02.500 --> 00:07:04.168
♪

137
00:07:04.268 --> 00:07:06.605
Okay. like you mean it.

138
00:07:06.705 --> 00:07:08.607
You guys. let me hear you.

139
00:07:08.707 --> 00:07:09.908
- (roars weakly)
- (meows)

140
00:07:10.008 --> 00:07:11.541
- GARCIA: What?
- (laughter)

141
00:07:11.542 --> 00:07:13.712
You call that a roar?
With passion.

142
00:07:13.812 --> 00:07:15.212
- Again.
- I'm sorry.

143
00:07:15.213 --> 00:07:16.547
This is a bit much.

144
00:07:16.648 --> 00:07:18.516
I feel like the claws
are enough.

145
00:07:18.617 --> 00:07:20.751
- How dare both of you.
- (phone chimes)

146
00:07:20.752 --> 00:07:22.085
Okay. now they're here.

147
00:07:22.086 --> 00:07:23.587
Okay. everyone.
get ready. get ready.

148
00:07:23.588 --> 00:07:25.724
- Think feral. okay? Here we go.
- Shh. shh.

149
00:07:26.591 --> 00:07:28.292
(door opening)

150
00:07:29.327 --> 00:07:30.929
- GARCIA: Congratulations!
- (others cheering)

151
00:07:31.062 --> 00:07:33.164
- (roaring)
- Congratulations!

152
00:07:34.032 --> 00:07:36.534
Wow. Thanks.

153
00:07:36.635 --> 00:07:38.637
Okay. your mom told you. right?

154
00:07:38.737 --> 00:07:41.940
I swear I did not.

155
00:07:42.040 --> 00:07:43.941
Your cars are around the corner.

156
00:07:43.942 --> 00:07:45.376
ROSSI:
Oh. they were.

157
00:07:45.476 --> 00:07:48.079
Okay. can we work on
our not-at-work stealthiness?

158
00:07:48.179 --> 00:07:50.080
No. no. it's cool.

159
00:07:50.081 --> 00:07:51.850
I like it. Thanks. Auntie P.

160
00:07:51.950 --> 00:07:53.685
- (group murmuring)
- So sweet.

161
00:07:53.785 --> 00:07:55.586
- Meow.
- (laughter)

162
00:07:55.687 --> 00:07:58.857
- This is impressive.
- (laughs)

163
00:07:59.791 --> 00:08:01.059
Ooh.

164
00:08:01.159 --> 00:08:04.696
Oh. so Spence told me
that he's happy for Henry

165
00:08:04.796 --> 00:08:08.432
but that he can still make
that call to Caltech.

166
00:08:08.532 --> 00:08:11.069
you know.
if he changes his mind.

167
00:08:11.936 --> 00:08:15.539
You have a lot to be proud of.

168
00:08:15.640 --> 00:08:19.644
You know who we're really here
to celebrate. right?

169
00:08:19.778 --> 00:08:21.780
You and Will.

170
00:08:23.281 --> 00:08:25.249
It's-it's been a long road.

171
00:08:30.588 --> 00:08:33.591
Heard you're getting roped
into another Voit sit-down.

172
00:08:33.692 --> 00:08:35.727
Oh. yeah. Should be interesting.

173
00:08:35.827 --> 00:08:37.828
- What does he want?
- No idea.

174
00:08:37.829 --> 00:08:40.264
The guy's gone silent since we
put him in the penalty box.

175
00:08:40.364 --> 00:08:42.734
(chuckling): Yeah.
he-he threw a bit of a tantrum

176
00:08:42.834 --> 00:08:44.468
when we limited his visitation.

177
00:08:44.602 --> 00:08:47.638
but this could be
an olive branch.

178
00:08:47.739 --> 00:08:50.775
Hey. chuckleheads.
What did we say? No shop talk.

179
00:08:50.875 --> 00:08:52.343
- Oh.
- Yeah.

180
00:08:52.476 --> 00:08:54.478
- All right.
- Busted.

181
00:08:54.578 --> 00:08:56.647
Okay. my pretties.
before work consumes us.

182
00:08:56.748 --> 00:08:58.282
let's take a family photo.

183
00:08:58.382 --> 00:09:02.020
Now. this happens
in groups of three.

184
00:09:02.120 --> 00:09:06.257
So. let the first one be
just our fabulous selves.

185
00:09:06.357 --> 00:09:08.893
(camera beeping)

186
00:09:12.096 --> 00:09:14.332
- (camera snaps)
- Okay.

187
00:09:14.432 --> 00:09:16.701
Now a silly one.
No. no. no. Bobcat.

188
00:09:16.835 --> 00:09:19.303
- Okay. uh. one. two...
- (camera beeping)

189
00:09:19.403 --> 00:09:21.773
- (phones buzzing. chiming)
- Oh.

190
00:09:23.107 --> 00:09:24.843
(camera continues beeping)

191
00:09:24.976 --> 00:09:26.144
Three.

192
00:09:26.244 --> 00:09:28.046
(camera snaps)

193
00:09:32.616 --> 00:09:34.719
Early this morning.
a teen wilderness troop

194
00:09:34.819 --> 00:09:36.855
was happily traversing
the hills and hollers

195
00:09:36.955 --> 00:09:40.291
of Darrington Nature Reserve in
Gardener County. West Virginia.

196
00:09:40.391 --> 00:09:42.692
when they tragically came
upon the body

197
00:09:42.693 --> 00:09:44.561
of 65-year-old Sharon Fussel.

198
00:09:44.562 --> 00:09:46.865
She joins Janis Kline
as the second woman

199
00:09:46.965 --> 00:09:49.500
in under two weeks
to be found in that area.

200
00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:51.269
Both victims had
their eyes glued open

201
00:09:51.369 --> 00:09:53.237
and their bodies
completely drained of blood.

202
00:09:53.371 --> 00:09:54.839
phlebotomist-style.

203
00:09:55.673 --> 00:09:57.075
Those women don't look dead.

204
00:09:57.208 --> 00:10:00.044
Yeah. more like someone
just shook them awake.

205
00:10:00.144 --> 00:10:01.879
Do we have a time of death
on either?

206
00:10:01.880 --> 00:10:04.715
No. And the local coroner
is just as perplexed

207
00:10:04.816 --> 00:10:06.717
about the state of these bodies
as we are.

208
00:10:06.818 --> 00:10:09.020
Locals should run
a tox screening

209
00:10:09.120 --> 00:10:10.488
for methanol and ethanol.

210
00:10:10.588 --> 00:10:11.890
Embalming fluid?

211
00:10:11.990 --> 00:10:13.391
Yeah. it helps
preserve the bodies.

212
00:10:13.524 --> 00:10:15.725
Maybe he's leaving them
in a state

213
00:10:15.726 --> 00:10:18.129
where he can come back
and enjoy.

214
00:10:18.897 --> 00:10:22.400
The victims are around
the same height. weight.

215
00:10:22.500 --> 00:10:24.567
Unsub has a physical type.

216
00:10:24.568 --> 00:10:27.205
But the victims are
ten years apart.

217
00:10:28.907 --> 00:10:30.941
There's no sign of assault.

218
00:10:30.942 --> 00:10:34.879
And he glued the eyes open
postmortem.

219
00:10:34.979 --> 00:10:36.480
What are you thinking?

220
00:10:37.748 --> 00:10:39.917
Unsubs will often
force their victims

221
00:10:39.918 --> 00:10:41.752
to watch what they're doing.

222
00:10:41.886 --> 00:10:43.754
This guy does it
after he kills them.

223
00:10:43.855 --> 00:10:45.689
Well. he must feel
more comfortable

224
00:10:45.790 --> 00:10:48.559
"interacting" with his victims
once they're dead.

225
00:10:48.659 --> 00:10:50.760
Gardener County has turned
the investigation over

226
00:10:50.761 --> 00:10:52.964
to the West Virginia Staties.

227
00:10:53.097 --> 00:10:55.399
JJ. Tyler. let's interview
friends and family.

228
00:10:55.499 --> 00:10:58.569
Dave. Luke.
review the autopsy reports.

229
00:10:58.669 --> 00:11:01.172
Disturbing this unsub's
dumping ground

230
00:11:01.272 --> 00:11:03.107
isn't gonna slow him down.

231
00:11:03.207 --> 00:11:05.076
♪ ♪

232
00:11:05.176 --> 00:11:06.609
(distant. indistinct
P.A. announcement)

233
00:11:06.610 --> 00:11:08.312
<i>LEWIS (sighs):
Elias.</i>

234
00:11:08.446 --> 00:11:09.981
We got your message.

235
00:11:10.081 --> 00:11:11.983
Let me get this straight...
you want us to break

236
00:11:12.083 --> 00:11:14.952
WITSEC protocol
to check in on your family.

237
00:11:14.953 --> 00:11:16.420
(stammering):
I get it.

238
00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:18.122
It's frowned upon
when government agencies

239
00:11:18.256 --> 00:11:19.858
shit in each other's
litter boxes.

240
00:11:19.958 --> 00:11:21.659
- but given the circumstances...
- LEWIS: Elias.

241
00:11:21.759 --> 00:11:23.294
You'd be doing them... you're
essentially cleaning up...

242
00:11:23.394 --> 00:11:26.330
Elias. one of our own went
into WITSEC. all right?

243
00:11:26.430 --> 00:11:27.465
It's safe.

244
00:11:27.565 --> 00:11:28.632
Yeah.

245
00:11:28.732 --> 00:11:30.633
One of your own.
This is different.

246
00:11:30.634 --> 00:11:33.170
When the world learned my name.
it put them at risk.

247
00:11:33.171 --> 00:11:35.306
You're right. and the Marshals
probably had to move

248
00:11:35.406 --> 00:11:37.041
heaven and earth
to get them new identities.

249
00:11:37.141 --> 00:11:39.510
But. unfortunately. those were
the cards they were dealt.

250
00:11:39.643 --> 00:11:42.380
Cards they were dealt by you.

251
00:11:44.082 --> 00:11:45.549
Now. where is this coming from?

252
00:11:45.649 --> 00:11:47.151
Do you have some reason
to believe

253
00:11:47.251 --> 00:11:49.153
that the Fan is gonna
target your family?

254
00:11:49.253 --> 00:11:52.924
I just want to know
they're safe.

255
00:11:53.791 --> 00:11:55.493
(sighs)

256
00:11:55.593 --> 00:11:57.827
(sighs)
We'll see what we can do.

257
00:11:57.828 --> 00:12:00.031
♪ ♪

258
00:12:01.966 --> 00:12:03.367
Yes. Mrs. Beltran.

259
00:12:03.501 --> 00:12:07.438
El Paso Oak is the solid oak
with wheat corners.

260
00:12:08.973 --> 00:12:10.474
Yes. I agree.

261
00:12:10.574 --> 00:12:13.211
And that wouldn't
cost you much more.

262
00:12:14.745 --> 00:12:18.349
(sighs) Well. let's see.

263
00:12:20.484 --> 00:12:23.854
Would you and your husband
be able to come by

264
00:12:23.988 --> 00:12:26.390
Friday morning?

265
00:12:27.725 --> 00:12:28.859
Perfect.

266
00:12:28.960 --> 00:12:32.563
Now. you have a wonderful
rest of your day.

267
00:12:34.966 --> 00:12:38.235
(beeping)

268
00:12:38.236 --> 00:12:40.404
<i>NARRATOR (on audiobook):
Chapter five.</i>

269
00:12:40.538 --> 00:12:43.207
<i>"Weathering the Storm."</i>

270
00:12:44.442 --> 00:12:48.446
<i>Losing a loved one
can make us feel powerless.</i>

271
00:12:49.247 --> 00:12:51.916
<i>Like we have no control.</i>

272
00:12:52.016 --> 00:12:55.886
<i>Now. picture yourself alone
on a sailboat</i>

273
00:12:56.020 --> 00:12:58.556
<i>that's crossing the ocean.</i>

274
00:12:58.656 --> 00:13:00.824
<i>Dark storm clouds surround you.</i>

275
00:13:00.925 --> 00:13:03.928
<i>Gale-force winds bearing down.</i>

276
00:13:04.062 --> 00:13:07.398
<i>Waves crashing over the sides.</i>

277
00:13:07.498 --> 00:13:09.767
<i>tossing the boat
left and right.</i>

278
00:13:09.900 --> 00:13:14.405
<i>Do you shut your eyes and hope
for the winds to change?</i>

279
00:13:14.505 --> 00:13:16.240
<i>For the storm to pass?</i>

280
00:13:17.041 --> 00:13:22.245
<i>Or do you take charge
and adjust the sails?</i>

281
00:13:22.246 --> 00:13:23.948
(beeps)

282
00:13:26.584 --> 00:13:29.919
- WOMAN: Help me!
- (banging)

283
00:13:29.920 --> 00:13:31.422
Anyone!

284
00:13:31.555 --> 00:13:34.457
Help me!

285
00:13:34.458 --> 00:13:37.260
Please. please. please help me!

286
00:13:37.261 --> 00:13:39.596
Please let me out!

287
00:13:39.597 --> 00:13:42.632
Please. Please.

288
00:13:42.633 --> 00:13:45.003
- (door opens)
- No.

289
00:13:45.836 --> 00:13:48.272
No more. No. (exhales)

290
00:13:48.372 --> 00:13:49.740
No more. okay?

291
00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:52.942
No more. No.

292
00:13:52.943 --> 00:13:55.446
What the fuck is... (whimpers)

293
00:13:55.579 --> 00:13:57.648
(crying): No.
What the fuck are you doing?

294
00:13:57.781 --> 00:13:59.583
What the fuck is wrong with you?

295
00:13:59.683 --> 00:14:02.086
You need to eat.

296
00:14:02.186 --> 00:14:04.788
(pained whimpering)

297
00:14:04.922 --> 00:14:08.126
(gurgles. coughs)

298
00:14:08.259 --> 00:14:09.927
(groans. spits)

299
00:14:10.961 --> 00:14:12.596
You sick fuck!

300
00:14:12.696 --> 00:14:14.598
(coughs. gags)

301
00:14:14.698 --> 00:14:17.535
(spitting. groaning)

302
00:14:19.637 --> 00:14:21.971
(sighs)

303
00:14:21.972 --> 00:14:23.507
That wasn't so bad.

304
00:14:23.607 --> 00:14:25.176
(breathing heavily)

305
00:14:28.446 --> 00:14:32.750
You're only making this harder
on yourself. my dear.

306
00:14:32.850 --> 00:14:34.152
(grunts)

307
00:14:34.285 --> 00:14:35.619
(screams)

308
00:14:35.719 --> 00:14:38.356
(whimpering. gurgling)

309
00:14:44.462 --> 00:14:45.496
<i>JJ:
We're so sorry</i>

310
00:14:45.596 --> 00:14:46.630
<i>for your loss. Mr. Fussel.</i>

311
00:14:46.730 --> 00:14:47.865
TED:
When they brought me in

312
00:14:47.998 --> 00:14:50.534
to identify Sharon.

313
00:14:50.634 --> 00:14:52.903
she still looked...

314
00:14:53.003 --> 00:14:54.572
so alive.

315
00:14:54.672 --> 00:14:58.176
Like I just needed to shake her.

316
00:14:58.309 --> 00:15:00.544
she'd get up and walk out.

317
00:15:01.512 --> 00:15:03.713
Mr. Fussel. what do you remember

318
00:15:03.714 --> 00:15:05.949
about the day
that Sharon went missing?

319
00:15:07.951 --> 00:15:10.954
It was the day
after my birthday.

320
00:15:11.055 --> 00:15:13.190
Two months ago.

321
00:15:13.191 --> 00:15:16.559
We'd just moved into
a senior-living community.

322
00:15:16.560 --> 00:15:19.097
which Sharon wasn't
too thrilled about.

323
00:15:20.498 --> 00:15:21.932
She'd gone out to the mailbox.

324
00:15:22.032 --> 00:15:24.701
which was
around the block there.

325
00:15:24.702 --> 00:15:26.637
That was the last time
I saw her.

326
00:15:27.405 --> 00:15:31.708
You know. I didn't think that
we needed to spend the money

327
00:15:31.709 --> 00:15:34.512
on one of those
security systems with cameras.

328
00:15:34.612 --> 00:15:36.247
This isn't your fault.

329
00:15:37.047 --> 00:15:40.584
Can you think of anyone who
would want to hurt your wife?

330
00:15:40.684 --> 00:15:42.986
Not a soul.

331
00:15:43.087 --> 00:15:44.722
Everybody adored her.

332
00:15:46.056 --> 00:15:48.326
I'm trying not to think about

333
00:15:48.426 --> 00:15:50.928
what he might have done
to her. you know?

334
00:15:51.762 --> 00:15:53.030
It's all so sickening.

335
00:15:55.399 --> 00:15:57.635
Why would he bother
to change her clothes?

336
00:15:58.936 --> 00:16:02.740
The clothes they found her in...
they weren't hers?

337
00:16:02.840 --> 00:16:04.408
No.

338
00:16:04.508 --> 00:16:06.910
When she left the house.
she was wearing. like.

339
00:16:07.010 --> 00:16:08.779
her jogging outfit.

340
00:16:09.913 --> 00:16:12.081
<i>JJ: So. we confirmed
with Janis Kline's son</i>

341
00:16:12.082 --> 00:16:13.616
the clothes she was wearing

342
00:16:13.617 --> 00:16:15.419
when she was found
weren't hers. either.

343
00:16:15.519 --> 00:16:18.289
Which means he's re-dressing
the victims postmortem.

344
00:16:18.389 --> 00:16:19.857
Now. I'm no fashion expert.

345
00:16:19.957 --> 00:16:23.093
but there don't seem to be
any striking similarities

346
00:16:23.194 --> 00:16:26.063
between the clothes
on Sharon and Janis.

347
00:16:26.164 --> 00:16:28.132
Yeah. now that you mention it.

348
00:16:28.232 --> 00:16:30.634
the style of the clothes
are distinct...

349
00:16:30.734 --> 00:16:32.436
from different decades. maybe.

350
00:16:32.570 --> 00:16:33.871
I see your point.

351
00:16:33.971 --> 00:16:36.140
You'd expect an unsub
to use a surrogate

352
00:16:36.240 --> 00:16:40.144
to re-create a specific fantasy
over and over.

353
00:16:41.312 --> 00:16:44.515
He's definitely preserving them
to be modeled for something.

354
00:16:44.615 --> 00:16:46.784
M.E. ran additional tox screens.

355
00:16:46.917 --> 00:16:50.288
and both victims.
along with embalming fluid.

356
00:16:50.388 --> 00:16:53.224
had near-lethal levels
of magnesium in their systems.

357
00:16:53.324 --> 00:16:55.493
I thought the cause of death
was exsanguination.

358
00:16:55.593 --> 00:16:56.960
It was.

359
00:16:57.060 --> 00:16:59.363
That means this guy was
force-feeding them magnesium

360
00:16:59.463 --> 00:17:01.965
- over several days.
- Why magnesium?

361
00:17:02.800 --> 00:17:06.370
It enhances hydration.
uh. reduces inflammation.

362
00:17:06.470 --> 00:17:09.473
Some people say it makes
your skin more radiant.

363
00:17:09.573 --> 00:17:12.676
All the better
for him to admire.

364
00:17:15.446 --> 00:17:18.416
<i>NARRATOR (on audiobook):
Grief introduces chaotic forces</i>

365
00:17:18.516 --> 00:17:21.785
<i>that can disrupt
our daily routines.</i>

366
00:17:21.885 --> 00:17:26.657
<i>But those turbulent forces
can be channeled.</i>

367
00:17:26.790 --> 00:17:30.794
<i>Rather than trying
to ignore your grief.</i>

368
00:17:30.894 --> 00:17:33.697
<i>try listening to it.</i>

369
00:17:34.798 --> 00:17:38.202
<i>The pain you feel is
the residual effect</i>

370
00:17:38.336 --> 00:17:40.404
<i>of loving someone.</i>

371
00:17:41.171 --> 00:17:43.840
<i>Just because they're
no longer with you</i>

372
00:17:43.841 --> 00:17:46.043
<i>doesn't mean
they can't continue</i>

373
00:17:46.176 --> 00:17:49.280
<i>to motivate and inspire you.</i>

374
00:17:50.214 --> 00:17:54.518
<i>But. in order to properly
channel those emotions.</i>

375
00:17:54.652 --> 00:17:58.021
<i>you should remember
this timeless maxim:</i>

376
00:17:58.121 --> 00:18:02.225
<i>We must accept
what we cannot control.</i>

377
00:18:02.226 --> 00:18:05.728
"We must accept

378
00:18:05.729 --> 00:18:08.899
what we cannot control."

379
00:18:15.906 --> 00:18:18.075
♪ ♪

380
00:18:20.143 --> 00:18:22.112
(flashbulb snaps)

381
00:18:24.648 --> 00:18:27.918
<i>PRENTISS: Voit wants us to find
his family in WITSEC.</i>

382
00:18:28.018 --> 00:18:29.552
What prompted this?

383
00:18:29.553 --> 00:18:32.890
Well. we think that it might
have something to do with...

384
00:18:32.990 --> 00:18:34.725
this man.

385
00:18:35.659 --> 00:18:38.762
He checked in as Joshua Ryan.
cousin of Alex. Deena's father.

386
00:18:38.896 --> 00:18:40.564
- Mm-hmm.
- REBECCA: He visited three times

387
00:18:40.664 --> 00:18:42.366
in three days.

388
00:18:42.466 --> 00:18:45.035
Watch what happened
on his last visit.

389
00:18:46.437 --> 00:18:49.607
LEWIS: We think that's a photo
of Voit's family.

390
00:18:49.707 --> 00:18:51.108
That's what got him spooked?

391
00:18:51.208 --> 00:18:53.911
Look. Voit tried to get
a message to the Fan.

392
00:18:54.011 --> 00:18:56.547
inviting him to come
visit him in prison.

393
00:18:57.348 --> 00:18:58.781
What if he did just that?

394
00:18:58.782 --> 00:19:01.319
He didn't sign the release
for the audio recording.

395
00:19:01.419 --> 00:19:03.287
and he came in
with ghost glasses.

396
00:19:03.387 --> 00:19:04.988
LEWIS:
They emitted an infrared light

397
00:19:05.088 --> 00:19:07.290
that blew out
the security cameras.

398
00:19:07.291 --> 00:19:08.458
PRENTISS:
Holy shit.

399
00:19:08.459 --> 00:19:09.960
- This is him.
- LEWIS: Yeah.

400
00:19:10.060 --> 00:19:12.430
Yeah. that's not all.
Look at this.

401
00:19:13.764 --> 00:19:14.965
See that keychain?

402
00:19:15.098 --> 00:19:16.300
It's an anime character.

403
00:19:16.434 --> 00:19:19.101
Extremely similar to the artwork

404
00:19:19.102 --> 00:19:22.272
that we found
in Victoria Everman's apartment.

405
00:19:22.373 --> 00:19:25.274
- A trophy from his first kill.
- LEWIS: I think so.

406
00:19:25.275 --> 00:19:27.276
REBECCA:
Do we really think it's possible

407
00:19:27.277 --> 00:19:29.947
the Fan could actually be
Alex Ryan's cousin?

408
00:19:30.047 --> 00:19:33.484
I think it's far more likely
the Fan pulled one over on Alex.

409
00:19:33.617 --> 00:19:36.486
but either way. we need to get
Alex in for questioning now.

410
00:19:36.487 --> 00:19:37.955
We're on it.

411
00:19:38.055 --> 00:19:40.190
♪ ♪

412
00:19:46.730 --> 00:19:50.934
ROSSI: Does it matter if your Fan knows
exactly where they are or not?

413
00:19:51.769 --> 00:19:55.105
Because. if there's a will.
there's a way.

414
00:19:55.906 --> 00:19:57.307
It's what I've been saying

415
00:19:57.441 --> 00:20:00.944
ever since they locked you up
in this place.

416
00:20:11.021 --> 00:20:14.692
I noticed you didn't mention
to Dr. Lewis

417
00:20:14.792 --> 00:20:17.661
that he showed up
to threaten your family.

418
00:20:17.761 --> 00:20:19.530
I asked her to check on them.

419
00:20:19.630 --> 00:20:21.865
Eh. if I didn't know
any better. I would say

420
00:20:21.999 --> 00:20:24.501
- you're up to your old tricks.
- I'm not.

421
00:20:24.502 --> 00:20:26.537
You know how I know?

422
00:20:26.637 --> 00:20:28.539
Because you go quiet

423
00:20:28.639 --> 00:20:31.375
and you start lying
to everybody.

424
00:20:31.475 --> 00:20:35.312
including yourself.

425
00:20:43.954 --> 00:20:46.123
(quiet chatter)

426
00:20:47.658 --> 00:20:51.894
As anyone who has been forced
to read Ayn Rand will tell you.

427
00:20:51.895 --> 00:20:54.031
awfulness comes in three parts.

428
00:20:54.131 --> 00:20:55.898
Another body
in Darrington Reserve?

429
00:20:55.899 --> 00:20:58.568
Nope. but a stone's throw away
in Fielder County.

430
00:20:58.569 --> 00:21:00.237
Our unsub's got
a new dumping ground.

431
00:21:00.337 --> 00:21:02.071
I'll get Dave
and head over there now.

432
00:21:02.072 --> 00:21:03.306
Yeah.

433
00:21:03.407 --> 00:21:05.374
REBECCA:
Thanks for coming in. Mr. Ryan.

434
00:21:05.375 --> 00:21:07.811
I know what
you're going to ask me.

435
00:21:08.712 --> 00:21:09.647
Do you?

436
00:21:09.747 --> 00:21:11.582
It's about my cousin. isn't it?

437
00:21:12.450 --> 00:21:14.117
Yes. it is.

438
00:21:15.553 --> 00:21:17.254
Look...

439
00:21:18.221 --> 00:21:21.223
I know that me and my ex-wife
are the only ones

440
00:21:21.224 --> 00:21:24.227
that were given permission
to speak to Voit...

441
00:21:25.529 --> 00:21:28.265
...but I swear
I-I couldn't do it.

442
00:21:29.166 --> 00:21:32.770
And when Joshua reached out.
it was like...

443
00:21:32.870 --> 00:21:34.972
the universe stepping in
to help me.

444
00:21:36.907 --> 00:21:39.576
I hadn't seen Joshua in 20...

445
00:21:39.577 --> 00:21:41.244
I don't know. maybe 30 years.

446
00:21:41.378 --> 00:21:43.614
And in all that time.
he got himself a...

447
00:21:43.714 --> 00:21:46.249
a PhD in criminology.

448
00:21:47.518 --> 00:21:49.219
Really?

449
00:21:49.319 --> 00:21:51.455
And so. I'm assuming that Joshua

450
00:21:51.589 --> 00:21:54.057
offered to speak to Voit
on your behalf?

451
00:21:55.292 --> 00:21:58.427
He said he wanted to write books
on serial killers.

452
00:21:58.428 --> 00:22:01.632
So it seemed like a good plan.

453
00:22:02.633 --> 00:22:07.104
After your cousin's visits.
did he reach out to you again?

454
00:22:07.204 --> 00:22:08.606
No. not yet. Why?

455
00:22:09.807 --> 00:22:11.642
Mr. Ryan. we don't believe
that the person

456
00:22:11.775 --> 00:22:15.479
that you interacted with was
actually your cousin Joshua.

457
00:22:18.081 --> 00:22:19.750
What?

458
00:22:21.218 --> 00:22:23.353
He knew everything
about my family.

459
00:22:24.287 --> 00:22:25.889
I'm sure that he did.

460
00:22:25.989 --> 00:22:29.126
Do you have any contact
information for this man?

461
00:22:31.094 --> 00:22:32.996
Uh. we...

462
00:22:33.096 --> 00:22:36.133
we only wrote emails
back and forth.

463
00:22:37.234 --> 00:22:41.204
The last one bounced...
bounced back for some reason.

464
00:22:45.075 --> 00:22:46.910
(sucks teeth)

465
00:22:47.811 --> 00:22:49.146
Who would do this?

466
00:22:49.246 --> 00:22:51.649
(Lewis takes deep breath)

467
00:22:57.254 --> 00:22:59.356
(siren wailing)

468
00:22:59.489 --> 00:23:00.990
They get an I.D. on the victim?

469
00:23:00.991 --> 00:23:03.293
State Police identified her
as Chloe Watts.

470
00:23:03.393 --> 00:23:05.563
She was reported missing
three weeks ago.

471
00:23:05.663 --> 00:23:08.098
Same as the two other victims
over in Gardener.

472
00:23:08.198 --> 00:23:10.200
Eyes glued open.

473
00:23:13.170 --> 00:23:15.372
TOOMEY: I can't be certain of cause
or time of death.

474
00:23:15.505 --> 00:23:17.841
but the staging
is clearly the same.

475
00:23:22.112 --> 00:23:23.914
How old was she?

476
00:23:24.047 --> 00:23:25.315
Forty-three.

477
00:23:25.415 --> 00:23:27.718
Well. finally.
a distinct pattern emerges.

478
00:23:27.851 --> 00:23:31.387
Each victim is getting younger
by a decade.

479
00:23:31.388 --> 00:23:33.557
You know. and the clothing style

480
00:23:33.691 --> 00:23:35.893
seems to get more dated
with each victim.

481
00:23:35.993 --> 00:23:37.561
It's as if he's
honoring someone.

482
00:23:37.661 --> 00:23:41.231
like a wife
or a family member who died.

483
00:23:41.364 --> 00:23:43.566
And if that's the case.

484
00:23:43.567 --> 00:23:45.903
these clothes
might very well be hers.

485
00:23:47.605 --> 00:23:49.106
They haven't been soaked
in bleach.

486
00:23:49.239 --> 00:23:51.273
That woman's DNA
might still be on them.

487
00:23:51.274 --> 00:23:52.742
Yeah. that's what
I'm betting on.

488
00:23:52.743 --> 00:23:54.410
Dr. Toomey.
we're gonna need to run

489
00:23:54.411 --> 00:23:56.279
a fiber analysis on her clothes.

490
00:23:56.379 --> 00:23:58.081
Absolutely.

491
00:24:04.454 --> 00:24:07.858
("O mio babbino caro" from
Puccini's <i>Gianni Schicchi</i> plays)

492
00:24:19.770 --> 00:24:22.973
(aria continues with
operatic singing in Italian)

493
00:24:23.106 --> 00:24:25.375
(aria continues playing
in other room)

494
00:24:42.926 --> 00:24:45.095
(grunting)

495
00:24:58.441 --> 00:25:00.810
(straining)

496
00:25:00.811 --> 00:25:02.179
(grunts)

497
00:25:02.312 --> 00:25:04.214
(panting):
Oh. fuck

498
00:25:16.093 --> 00:25:18.228
(panting)

499
00:25:29.439 --> 00:25:31.541
(grunts)

500
00:25:46.023 --> 00:25:48.759
(panting)

501
00:25:58.101 --> 00:25:59.703
(lighter flicks)

502
00:26:01.872 --> 00:26:04.041
(grunts quietly)

503
00:26:05.208 --> 00:26:07.745
(muffled grunting)

504
00:26:09.046 --> 00:26:11.381
(muffled screaming)

505
00:26:11.481 --> 00:26:13.216
(aria continues)

506
00:26:13.350 --> 00:26:15.384
(inhales deeply)

507
00:26:15.385 --> 00:26:16.719
(exhales)

508
00:26:16.720 --> 00:26:19.889
(muffled groaning)

509
00:26:19.890 --> 00:26:22.392
(muffled screaming)

510
00:26:23.226 --> 00:26:25.628
I have so much to tell you.

511
00:26:26.496 --> 00:26:28.198
(aria continues)

512
00:26:28.298 --> 00:26:31.201
(muffled screaming)

513
00:26:33.336 --> 00:26:35.705
(pained yelling)

514
00:26:35.806 --> 00:26:37.841
(whimpering)

515
00:26:49.953 --> 00:26:52.089
♪ ♪

516
00:26:54.191 --> 00:26:56.226
(dribbles ball)

517
00:27:00.898 --> 00:27:02.465
(ball drops through net)

518
00:27:02.565 --> 00:27:04.567
(ball bouncing)

519
00:27:06.403 --> 00:27:09.039
♪ ♪

520
00:27:09.139 --> 00:27:10.740
(clears throat quietly)

521
00:27:19.049 --> 00:27:21.018
(sighs)

522
00:27:30.861 --> 00:27:33.563
<i>- HOLLY: Dad. stop talking.</i>
- (tires squeal)

523
00:27:33.663 --> 00:27:34.764
(sighs):
Okay.

524
00:27:34.898 --> 00:27:36.399
I can't drive and listen
at the same time.

525
00:27:36.533 --> 00:27:39.736
No. hey. hey.
you are doing great.

526
00:27:39.837 --> 00:27:41.437
What's the point of this?

527
00:27:41.438 --> 00:27:43.440
Driverless cars
are like two years away.

528
00:27:43.573 --> 00:27:46.609
Oh. my God. do you know
what driving represents?

529
00:27:46.709 --> 00:27:49.579
Our addiction to fossil fuels?

530
00:27:50.580 --> 00:27:52.582
Driving represents freedom.

531
00:27:52.715 --> 00:27:54.417
- (scoffs)
- Hey.

532
00:27:54.517 --> 00:27:57.454
A couple years. your world is
going to open up.

533
00:27:57.587 --> 00:27:59.689
and there's gonna be no more
homework. no more curfew...

534
00:27:59.789 --> 00:28:02.159
No angsty parents
peeking over my shoulder.

535
00:28:02.259 --> 00:28:04.127
No angsty parents.

536
00:28:04.227 --> 00:28:05.963
Life is gonna
give you room to run.

537
00:28:06.063 --> 00:28:07.796
and I'm not gonna be here
to ride shotgun.

538
00:28:07.797 --> 00:28:11.668
so I need to know that you are
ready to take the wheel. okay?

539
00:28:11.768 --> 00:28:13.170
Got it.

540
00:28:13.937 --> 00:28:15.305
One little problem.

541
00:28:15.405 --> 00:28:16.974
- Hmm?
- I don't have my permit.

542
00:28:17.107 --> 00:28:18.608
What do we tell Mom?

543
00:28:19.576 --> 00:28:21.611
It'll be our secret.

544
00:28:23.313 --> 00:28:25.582
What she doesn't know
can't hurt her.

545
00:28:26.449 --> 00:28:28.551
Right. Okay.

546
00:28:28.651 --> 00:28:30.452
- (sighs): Okay.
- Hands at ten and two.

547
00:28:30.453 --> 00:28:33.290
And just try to lay off
the brake this time. all right?

548
00:28:33.390 --> 00:28:36.493
(sighs) Yeah. Dad. I got it.

549
00:28:37.394 --> 00:28:39.129
(sighs)

550
00:28:40.163 --> 00:28:41.631
- (buzzing)
- (door clanks open)

551
00:28:41.731 --> 00:28:44.001
(indistinct shouting
in distance)

552
00:28:47.971 --> 00:28:49.706
Elias.

553
00:28:50.941 --> 00:28:53.376
Elias. we know
the Fan visited you

554
00:28:53.476 --> 00:28:55.512
and threatened your family.

555
00:28:55.645 --> 00:28:57.414
He had a picture of them.

556
00:28:57.514 --> 00:28:59.816
It could've been a part
of a court record.

557
00:28:59.917 --> 00:29:02.319
He could've lifted it
off a police server.

558
00:29:02.419 --> 00:29:05.022
REBECCA: Director of the U.S. Marshals
assured me

559
00:29:05.122 --> 00:29:07.724
that whatever threat
the Fan made was a bluff.

560
00:29:07.824 --> 00:29:10.859
Your family's new identities
have never been compromised.

561
00:29:10.860 --> 00:29:13.496
Nevertheless.
the Marshals are increasing

562
00:29:13.596 --> 00:29:16.499
the protective detail
on your family as we speak.

563
00:29:16.599 --> 00:29:17.700
They are safe.

564
00:29:17.800 --> 00:29:19.335
LEWIS:
And you can help us.

565
00:29:19.336 --> 00:29:22.205
All right? Because you just
sat down with this man.

566
00:29:22.305 --> 00:29:24.007
Tell us what you talked about.

567
00:29:24.107 --> 00:29:26.809
♪ ♪

568
00:29:26.910 --> 00:29:28.545
I need to see them first.

569
00:29:29.312 --> 00:29:31.814
We swear we would if we could.

570
00:29:31.915 --> 00:29:35.217
but cooperating with the BAU
also helps ensure their safety.

571
00:29:35.218 --> 00:29:37.687
Yeah. or it just plays
into his hands.

572
00:29:37.787 --> 00:29:39.822
All right.

573
00:29:39.923 --> 00:29:42.159
I know you're scared.

574
00:29:42.259 --> 00:29:44.061
Because even though
you pride yourself

575
00:29:44.161 --> 00:29:47.030
on being able to profile
serial killer behavior.

576
00:29:47.130 --> 00:29:50.400
you have been wrong about
the Fan from the very start.

577
00:29:50.500 --> 00:29:52.369
You underestimated the pace
of his evolution.

578
00:29:52.469 --> 00:29:54.171
You misinterpreted
his motivations.

579
00:29:54.271 --> 00:29:56.473
This guy is creeping around
in your blind spot.

580
00:29:56.573 --> 00:29:58.942
He knows it. and that's why
he can provoke you.

581
00:29:59.042 --> 00:30:01.378
REBECCA:
That could be part of his game. too.

582
00:30:01.478 --> 00:30:02.545
like a shell game.

583
00:30:02.679 --> 00:30:04.713
Right?
While we're focusing on you

584
00:30:04.714 --> 00:30:06.083
and your family. he's free

585
00:30:06.216 --> 00:30:08.451
- to pursue his real goal.
- Yeah.

586
00:30:08.551 --> 00:30:11.588
And if you're right. then
everything he shared with me

587
00:30:11.688 --> 00:30:14.724
is just gonna lead you
into a trap. isn't it?

588
00:30:14.857 --> 00:30:17.060
♪

589
00:30:18.628 --> 00:30:20.230
(Voit sighs)

590
00:30:22.199 --> 00:30:23.566
- (computer chimes)
- (gasps)

591
00:30:23.666 --> 00:30:25.002
Fresh from the West Virginia
Crime Lab oven.

592
00:30:25.102 --> 00:30:26.736
we have confirmation
that there was DNA

593
00:30:26.869 --> 00:30:29.571
of an unidentified woman on the
clothes of all three victims.

594
00:30:29.572 --> 00:30:31.074
No hit from CODIS just yet.

595
00:30:31.174 --> 00:30:34.743
but they did send us
a clear genetic profile.

596
00:30:34.744 --> 00:30:36.745
Basically. she's Caucasian.
medium build.

597
00:30:36.746 --> 00:30:38.780
with dark hair and blue eyes.

598
00:30:38.781 --> 00:30:40.017
Which matches our victims.

599
00:30:40.117 --> 00:30:41.384
This woman would've been ripped

600
00:30:41.484 --> 00:30:43.419
from our unsub's life
in a terrible way.

601
00:30:43.420 --> 00:30:45.322
Name that tragedy.

602
00:30:45.422 --> 00:30:47.190
Accident. homicide. suicide.

603
00:30:47.290 --> 00:30:49.492
And these women are
some sort of a tribute to her.

604
00:30:49.592 --> 00:30:51.461
Okay. but why go
to such great lengths

605
00:30:51.561 --> 00:30:53.630
to preserve them
only to discard them?

606
00:30:53.730 --> 00:30:54.998
GREEN:
I think I know why.

607
00:30:55.098 --> 00:30:56.765
There were trace amounts
of acetic acid

608
00:30:56.766 --> 00:30:58.301
found on Chloe Watts's body.

609
00:30:58.435 --> 00:31:00.769
Acetic acid is used
in the development process

610
00:31:00.770 --> 00:31:02.839
of old-school black-and-white
film photography.

611
00:31:02.939 --> 00:31:05.975
So he's keeping the memory
of this woman alive

612
00:31:06.076 --> 00:31:09.046
by photographing these victims
in her image.

613
00:31:09.812 --> 00:31:12.481
Penelope. can you start
culling through the names

614
00:31:12.482 --> 00:31:15.451
of embalmers. undertakers
and morticians

615
00:31:15.452 --> 00:31:17.020
that reside
in the tri-county area?

616
00:31:17.120 --> 00:31:19.422
- Yeah.
- JJ: And focus your search on

617
00:31:19.522 --> 00:31:21.658
those who've lost a close
female family member.

618
00:31:21.758 --> 00:31:23.326
Spreading out
my digital tentacles now.

619
00:31:23.460 --> 00:31:25.395
- (computer chimes)
- Which. oops. I have to retract.

620
00:31:25.495 --> 00:31:26.795
'cause we just got
a missing persons report

621
00:31:26.796 --> 00:31:27.797
from Fielder County.

622
00:31:27.930 --> 00:31:30.300
Grace Menard. 27.

623
00:31:30.433 --> 00:31:31.701
That tracks
with his victimology.

624
00:31:31.801 --> 00:31:32.802
How long has she been gone?

625
00:31:32.902 --> 00:31:34.137
Uh. her mom filed the report.

626
00:31:34.271 --> 00:31:36.306
The last time they talked
was three days ago.

627
00:31:37.107 --> 00:31:39.642
If the unsub took her.
she doesn't have much time.

628
00:31:39.742 --> 00:31:42.645
- The Platinum Series.
- (pencil scratching on paper)

629
00:31:42.779 --> 00:31:44.814
Excellent choice.

630
00:31:46.549 --> 00:31:48.518
Well. as my mother always said.

631
00:31:48.618 --> 00:31:52.488
preparedness is
next to godliness.

632
00:31:52.489 --> 00:31:54.357
♪ ♪

633
00:31:54.491 --> 00:31:56.693
(breathing heavily)

634
00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:05.702
Thank you.

635
00:32:06.536 --> 00:32:09.639
I feel as if
she's still with me every day.

636
00:32:19.749 --> 00:32:21.951
(breathing heavily)

637
00:32:30.160 --> 00:32:31.461
(yells)

638
00:32:33.696 --> 00:32:36.899
(chiming. vibrating)

639
00:32:37.700 --> 00:32:39.402
Of course. That's...

640
00:32:39.536 --> 00:32:41.904
That's very kind of you to say.
Mrs. Buchwalter.

641
00:32:42.038 --> 00:32:44.407
You have a wonderful
rest of your day.

642
00:32:45.542 --> 00:32:47.444
(sighs)

643
00:32:53.516 --> 00:32:55.585
(footfalls descending stairs)

644
00:32:58.488 --> 00:33:00.657
♪ ♪

645
00:33:09.065 --> 00:33:11.368
(glass crunching)

646
00:33:17.507 --> 00:33:19.275
(screams)

647
00:33:19.276 --> 00:33:21.110
(groans)

648
00:33:23.313 --> 00:33:25.615
(shuddering breaths)

649
00:33:27.684 --> 00:33:29.118
(gasping)

650
00:33:29.219 --> 00:33:30.720
(doorknob jiggling)

651
00:33:30.820 --> 00:33:32.754
(grunts) Son of a bitch.

652
00:33:32.755 --> 00:33:34.957
(panting)

653
00:33:37.093 --> 00:33:38.661
(sniffles)

654
00:33:40.763 --> 00:33:42.299
(sniffles)

655
00:33:56.746 --> 00:33:58.781
(whimpers)

656
00:34:02.319 --> 00:34:06.022
- (whooshing. electrical buzzing)
- (grunts. whimpers)

657
00:34:06.122 --> 00:34:07.990
(thuds)

658
00:34:11.794 --> 00:34:13.930
(buzzing stops)

659
00:34:16.266 --> 00:34:18.501
Okay. dreamboats. based on
the wonderful parameters...

660
00:34:18.601 --> 00:34:19.969
- (footsteps approaching)
- Hi. Come on in.

661
00:34:20.069 --> 00:34:22.304
...that you gave me.
I was able to uncover

662
00:34:22.305 --> 00:34:25.675
the recent. untimely death
of a one Katrina Bancroft.

663
00:34:25.775 --> 00:34:28.478
She died in a single-car
accident six months ago.

664
00:34:28.578 --> 00:34:29.846
It says here
she drove off a cliff

665
00:34:29.946 --> 00:34:31.248
near the Darrington Reserve.

666
00:34:31.348 --> 00:34:32.715
where the first two victims
were found.

667
00:34:32.815 --> 00:34:34.050
Suicide.

668
00:34:34.150 --> 00:34:35.685
Yeah. that's what
the authorities deemed it as.

669
00:34:35.818 --> 00:34:37.887
especially because her car
was filled to the brim

670
00:34:37.987 --> 00:34:39.021
with personal items.

671
00:34:39.155 --> 00:34:40.323
Body burned so badly

672
00:34:40.457 --> 00:34:42.992
they needed dental records
to identify her.

673
00:34:43.092 --> 00:34:44.694
ALVEZ:
She was the owner and operator

674
00:34:44.794 --> 00:34:46.629
of a funeral home
in Fielder County.

675
00:34:46.729 --> 00:34:48.631
Yes. and that was bequeathed
to her one and only son.

676
00:34:48.731 --> 00:34:51.368
Marvin Bancroft.
who filed multiple claims

677
00:34:51.501 --> 00:34:53.636
on his mom's insurance.
all which were denied.

678
00:34:53.736 --> 00:34:55.872
demanding compensation
for the. quote-unquote.

679
00:34:56.005 --> 00:34:57.774
"priceless portraits"
of his mother

680
00:34:57.874 --> 00:34:59.742
that were taken every year
on her birthday

681
00:34:59.842 --> 00:35:01.544
for the better part of 68 years.

682
00:35:01.644 --> 00:35:03.012
Do we have an address
for Marvin?

683
00:35:03.112 --> 00:35:05.213
Of course we do.
I just sent it to your phones.

684
00:35:05.214 --> 00:35:07.215
Have the deputies
meet us on site.

685
00:35:07.216 --> 00:35:09.018
GARCIA:
You got it.

686
00:35:10.420 --> 00:35:12.589
(birds chirping)

687
00:35:32.709 --> 00:35:35.545
(playing "Ave Maria")

688
00:35:47.824 --> 00:35:50.693
("Ave Maria" continues)

689
00:36:11.180 --> 00:36:14.116
♪ ♪

690
00:36:38.741 --> 00:36:40.943
♪

691
00:36:49.552 --> 00:36:51.320
(sniffs)

692
00:36:56.493 --> 00:36:57.960
What the fuck?

693
00:36:58.060 --> 00:37:01.163
Hold still. please.

694
00:37:06.569 --> 00:37:08.538
What is this?

695
00:37:09.305 --> 00:37:11.107
- What are you doing?
- Shh.

696
00:37:11.207 --> 00:37:12.642
Don't worry.

697
00:37:12.742 --> 00:37:16.713
I promise you
that you are in good hands.

698
00:37:29.258 --> 00:37:30.993
What the fuck are you doing?

699
00:37:31.093 --> 00:37:32.995
(liquid pouring)

700
00:37:33.095 --> 00:37:34.897
Hey. hey.

701
00:37:34.997 --> 00:37:36.933
Hey. hey. hey. hey.
that-that's...

702
00:37:37.033 --> 00:37:39.502
that's-that's your mom
in the other room?

703
00:37:40.503 --> 00:37:41.804
Pardon?

704
00:37:42.639 --> 00:37:44.040
In there. in...

705
00:37:44.140 --> 00:37:45.475
I'm right. aren't I?

706
00:37:45.575 --> 00:37:48.678
And-and-and she-she...
she passed away?

707
00:37:51.180 --> 00:37:52.882
Yeah?

708
00:37:53.716 --> 00:37:55.184
I'm so sorry.

709
00:37:56.018 --> 00:37:58.354
I'm so sorry for your loss.

710
00:37:59.456 --> 00:38:01.057
What was her name?

711
00:38:01.190 --> 00:38:04.561
- Katrina.
- Katrina.

712
00:38:05.995 --> 00:38:08.530
Um. what did...

713
00:38:08.531 --> 00:38:11.100
It's a beautiful name.
What did she name you?

714
00:38:12.835 --> 00:38:15.538
- Marvin.
- Marvin.

715
00:38:16.539 --> 00:38:19.375
Yeah. Marvin. Marvin.

716
00:38:19.476 --> 00:38:23.345
My mom named me Grace.
(chuckles)

717
00:38:23.446 --> 00:38:25.715
(laughing):
Like the blessing.

718
00:38:27.950 --> 00:38:29.885
(Grace takes deep breath)

719
00:38:29.886 --> 00:38:31.621
I'm sure your mom is really...

720
00:38:31.721 --> 00:38:34.023
really. really proud
of you. Marvin.

721
00:38:38.394 --> 00:38:40.262
Yeah.

722
00:38:41.230 --> 00:38:43.399
- (crying): Thank you. Grace.
- (chuckling): Yeah.

723
00:38:43.533 --> 00:38:45.234
Mm-hmm.

724
00:38:48.270 --> 00:38:51.240
(whimpering):
No. no. no. no.

725
00:38:52.374 --> 00:38:54.075
No. no. no. no. no.

726
00:38:54.076 --> 00:38:56.411
Hey. Hey.

727
00:38:56.412 --> 00:38:58.080
Marvin.

728
00:38:59.616 --> 00:39:03.085
You do not have to do
all of this. Marvin.

729
00:39:03.219 --> 00:39:04.420
Okay?

730
00:39:04.554 --> 00:39:06.255
(panting)

731
00:39:06.355 --> 00:39:08.257
Okay? (whimpers)

732
00:39:09.526 --> 00:39:11.193
(grunts) No.

733
00:39:11.293 --> 00:39:13.763
(whimpering)

734
00:39:13.863 --> 00:39:15.898
(sobbing)

735
00:39:17.867 --> 00:39:20.637
(sobbing):
I'm begging you. Marvin.

736
00:39:37.587 --> 00:39:39.889
- (siren wailing)
- (tires squealing)

737
00:39:45.094 --> 00:39:47.363
♪ ♪

738
00:39:54.236 --> 00:39:56.005
ROSSI:
Tyler and I will cover the back.

739
00:39:56.138 --> 00:39:58.541
You two take the front.

740
00:40:07.550 --> 00:40:09.085
(lock clicks)

741
00:40:17.526 --> 00:40:19.395
(chimes. vibrates)

742
00:40:20.229 --> 00:40:21.530
No.

743
00:40:21.664 --> 00:40:23.733
No. no. no. no!

744
00:40:29.171 --> 00:40:30.739
(burbling)

745
00:40:30.740 --> 00:40:32.041
FBI!

746
00:40:34.276 --> 00:40:35.912
JJ:
Marvin Bancroft!

747
00:40:39.215 --> 00:40:41.851
Grace? Grace.
you're gonna be okay.

748
00:40:41.951 --> 00:40:44.153
You're all right. okay?
Just breathe.

749
00:40:44.253 --> 00:40:45.588
We need medical.

750
00:40:46.455 --> 00:40:48.190
All right?

751
00:40:52.494 --> 00:40:55.097
- Come on. get her out of here.
- (Grace grunting weakly)

752
00:41:02.939 --> 00:41:05.073
Put the gun down
and turn around.

753
00:41:05.074 --> 00:41:06.776
I can't leave her.

754
00:41:06.909 --> 00:41:08.444
JJ:
You're not leaving her.

755
00:41:08.577 --> 00:41:10.913
She's always with you.

756
00:41:12.081 --> 00:41:13.816
Yes. she is.

757
00:41:13.916 --> 00:41:16.619
That's-that's right.

758
00:41:16.719 --> 00:41:20.690
See. Marvin. I... I'm a mom.

759
00:41:20.790 --> 00:41:23.559
And I know moms never

760
00:41:23.660 --> 00:41:27.263
want to see their kids
get hurt.

761
00:41:28.698 --> 00:41:33.435
So I'm gonna need you
to just put the gun down.

762
00:41:37.473 --> 00:41:40.176
"We must accept
what we can't control."

763
00:41:53.622 --> 00:41:55.825
(exhales)

764
00:42:00.162 --> 00:42:02.198
(kicks gun away)

765
00:42:25.988 --> 00:42:27.989
(siren wails quietly)

766
00:42:27.990 --> 00:42:30.192
♪ ♪

767
00:42:35.998 --> 00:42:37.767
<i>JJ:
"There is an enduring tenderness</i>

768
00:42:37.867 --> 00:42:39.635
<i>"in the love of a mother
to a son</i>

769
00:42:39.736 --> 00:42:42.705
<i>that transcends all other
affections of the heart."</i>

770
00:42:42.839 --> 00:42:44.741
<i>Washington Irving.</i>

771
00:42:44.841 --> 00:42:47.376
GARCIA:
Oh. look at that gorgeous creature.

772
00:42:47.509 --> 00:42:49.879
- (gasps)
- (JJ sighs)

773
00:42:50.012 --> 00:42:51.881
JJ:
Okay. I promised myself

774
00:42:51.981 --> 00:42:54.216
I would hold off
on reminiscing. but...

775
00:42:54.350 --> 00:42:57.186
Oh. come on.
Indulge. my sweet friend.

776
00:42:57.319 --> 00:42:59.555
- Indulge.
- (door opens)

777
00:43:02.792 --> 00:43:05.194
(gasps) Yes.

778
00:43:05.294 --> 00:43:07.196
JJ:
Henry.

779
00:43:07.997 --> 00:43:09.065
GARCIA:
Oh. yes.

780
00:43:09.165 --> 00:43:12.268
The handsome plane has landed.

781
00:43:13.535 --> 00:43:15.037
Where did you get the suit?

782
00:43:15.137 --> 00:43:17.940
It was a wave
of my fairy godmother wand.

783
00:43:18.040 --> 00:43:19.241
An early graduation present.

784
00:43:19.341 --> 00:43:20.576
and Luke was nice enough
to pick it up.

785
00:43:20.709 --> 00:43:22.745
It's classy. right?

786
00:43:25.647 --> 00:43:27.750
(sighs):
Oh. God. you...

787
00:43:27.850 --> 00:43:29.918
you look...

788
00:43:29.919 --> 00:43:31.587
so grown-up. (chuckles)

789
00:43:31.720 --> 00:43:33.255
- HENRY: Mom.
- What?

790
00:43:33.355 --> 00:43:35.191
You're doing the thing again.

791
00:43:35.992 --> 00:43:38.795
(laughing):
Deal with it. okay? Come here.

792
00:43:43.032 --> 00:43:45.034
Um. I'm hungry.

793
00:43:45.134 --> 00:43:47.169
Mm. Of course you are.

794
00:43:47.269 --> 00:43:48.771
That makes two of us.

795
00:43:48.905 --> 00:43:51.540
I told the rest of the team
to meet us at Verano. so...

796
00:43:51.640 --> 00:43:52.909
Well. it's too late now.

797
00:43:53.042 --> 00:43:54.410
(Italian accent):
Never too late for Verano's.

798
00:43:54.543 --> 00:43:55.778
(normal accent):
Come on. I'm...

799
00:43:55.912 --> 00:43:57.445
They're gonna be there.
I'm paying.

800
00:43:57.446 --> 00:43:58.781
Well. then I'll take care
of the apps and the zerts.

801
00:43:58.915 --> 00:44:00.282
- Great.
- Can I change. then?

802
00:44:00.382 --> 00:44:01.917
ALVEZ:
What. are you crazy?

803
00:44:01.918 --> 00:44:04.921
No way. man.
You got to take it for a spin.

804
00:44:05.021 --> 00:44:06.088
Come on. Let's go.

805
00:44:06.222 --> 00:44:07.423
- (hushed): Yes!
- ALVEZ: All right?

806
00:44:07.556 --> 00:44:09.458
- (door opens)
- Gonna get my stuff.

807
00:44:09.591 --> 00:44:11.460
It's exciting.

808
00:44:11.560 --> 00:44:14.763
Oh. and with the back of it.
Oh. this is gonna be great.

809
00:44:17.199 --> 00:44:19.768
<i>PRENTISS: You know. I can't help
thinking there's a method</i>

810
00:44:19.869 --> 00:44:24.006
behind the Fan's madness.
because he is consistent.

811
00:44:24.106 --> 00:44:25.908
Each time he makes us commit

812
00:44:26.008 --> 00:44:27.608
to heading in one direction.
he dekes.

813
00:44:27.609 --> 00:44:30.146
So. let's go back over
the timeline again.

814
00:44:30.279 --> 00:44:31.612
Absolutely.

815
00:44:31.613 --> 00:44:35.283
Eight weeks ago. the Fan kills
Victoria Everman.

816
00:44:35.284 --> 00:44:37.486
♪ ♪

817
00:44:38.787 --> 00:44:40.823
(yelps. groans)

818
00:44:40.957 --> 00:44:43.325
- (grunting)
- (whimpering)

819
00:44:46.963 --> 00:44:48.697
(sighs)

820
00:44:49.631 --> 00:44:52.201
<i>PRENTISS:
Strangles her.</i>

821
00:44:53.535 --> 00:44:55.037
<i>And takes a souvenir.</i>

822
00:44:55.137 --> 00:44:58.941
As far as we know. that's
an isolated act of violence.

823
00:44:59.041 --> 00:45:00.642
But one week after that.

824
00:45:00.742 --> 00:45:02.879
Voit goes on
Brian Garrity's podcast.

825
00:45:02.979 --> 00:45:04.513
<i>VOIT:
There's nothing</i>

826
00:45:04.613 --> 00:45:05.982
romantic about me.

827
00:45:06.082 --> 00:45:07.483
It's sad how pathetic I am.

828
00:45:07.583 --> 00:45:10.086
<i>but you know who's
even more pathetic?</i>

829
00:45:10.186 --> 00:45:11.653
Someone who makes
a show about it.

830
00:45:11.753 --> 00:45:14.822
<i>- And anyone who listens to it.</i>
- (banging)

831
00:45:14.823 --> 00:45:18.527
Which opens an entirely new
can of worms.

832
00:45:20.029 --> 00:45:22.198
<i>The Fan is clearly innervated.</i>

833
00:45:23.532 --> 00:45:28.537
<i>And he responds a week later
by sending a message to Voit.</i>

834
00:45:33.342 --> 00:45:36.545
<i>A week after that.
he sends Voit</i>

835
00:45:36.645 --> 00:45:38.680
<i>the photos of Laura Boyd.</i>

836
00:45:39.681 --> 00:45:43.285
Two days after that.
he kidnaps Laura's ex.

837
00:45:43.385 --> 00:45:45.254
<i>Lance Kingston.</i>

838
00:45:48.524 --> 00:45:49.992
<i>The Fan uses Lance</i>

839
00:45:50.092 --> 00:45:52.227
<i>as a proxy to try
to communicate with Voit.</i>

840
00:45:52.228 --> 00:45:55.464
<i>and then he punishes him
by branding him</i>

841
00:45:55.564 --> 00:45:58.367
<i>over and over again
with the same word</i>

842
00:45:58.467 --> 00:46:00.736
<i>Voit used to describe him:</i>

843
00:46:00.869 --> 00:46:02.939
<i>- "pathetic."
- LEWIS: Hmm.</i>

844
00:46:03.039 --> 00:46:05.774
Then silence for another week.

845
00:46:05.874 --> 00:46:10.711
Until he risks everything
by talking to Voit face-to-face.

846
00:46:10.712 --> 00:46:13.149
<i>And threatened his family.</i>

847
00:46:14.783 --> 00:46:16.385
Where'd you get that?

848
00:46:16.485 --> 00:46:20.089
Presumably to poke the bear.
but the question is: Why?

849
00:46:20.189 --> 00:46:23.092
Do you think that he knew
we were out of town?

850
00:46:23.192 --> 00:46:25.161
- I wouldn't put it past him.
- Hmm.

851
00:46:25.261 --> 00:46:28.965
Now. I understand
the simmering psychopathy

852
00:46:29.065 --> 00:46:32.935
that led inevitably to him
murdering Victoria Everman.

853
00:46:33.035 --> 00:46:35.604
I understand his desire
to gain the attention

854
00:46:35.737 --> 00:46:39.907
of one of the most notorious
serial killers of all time.

855
00:46:39.908 --> 00:46:41.243
I understand what it means

856
00:46:41.377 --> 00:46:43.679
to have his heart broken
by his idol.

857
00:46:43.779 --> 00:46:47.950
But what I don't get is
Laura and Lance.

858
00:46:48.850 --> 00:46:52.521
<i>Why do these two play
such a key role in</i>

859
00:46:52.621 --> 00:46:54.356
the Fan's psychodrama?

860
00:46:54.456 --> 00:46:56.858
I mean. they have to be
connected to Voit somehow.

861
00:46:56.959 --> 00:46:58.427
But they aren't.

862
00:46:58.527 --> 00:47:00.429
Maybe to his family.

863
00:47:00.529 --> 00:47:02.564
But not before
they joined WITSEC.

864
00:47:02.664 --> 00:47:03.799
Otherwise. there's no way

865
00:47:03.932 --> 00:47:05.134
we wouldn't have made
that connection.

866
00:47:05.234 --> 00:47:06.767
Yeah. you're right.

867
00:47:06.768 --> 00:47:09.405
And neither Laura nor Lance
see any connection. either.

868
00:47:09.505 --> 00:47:11.772
No. they don't.
and neither does Voit.

869
00:47:11.773 --> 00:47:13.275
(sighs) Unless...

870
00:47:13.409 --> 00:47:15.777
(clicks tongue)
Unless Voit's lying to us.

871
00:47:16.645 --> 00:47:18.247
I don't think he is lying.

872
00:47:18.347 --> 00:47:20.182
I-I think he's wrong.

873
00:47:21.050 --> 00:47:22.651
It's what you said...

874
00:47:22.751 --> 00:47:25.287
this guy has thrown Voit
for a loop.

875
00:47:25.387 --> 00:47:26.555
I mean. he is definitely
living rent-free

876
00:47:26.655 --> 00:47:27.990
in Voit's head right now.

877
00:47:28.090 --> 00:47:31.393
So. based on the murder
of Victoria Everman.

878
00:47:31.493 --> 00:47:34.130
the Fan's profile suggests

879
00:47:34.230 --> 00:47:37.033
Laura Boyd means something
to him.

880
00:47:38.400 --> 00:47:41.403
The U.S. Marshals stopped
monitoring Laura weeks ago.

881
00:47:41.503 --> 00:47:42.838
Same with Lance.

882
00:47:42.938 --> 00:47:44.273
As soon as he was discharged
from the hospital.

883
00:47:44.373 --> 00:47:46.775
(sighs)
Rebecca's got to make a call.

884
00:47:46.875 --> 00:47:49.978
Okay. right now. I'd say
Laura Boyd is our priority.

885
00:47:50.112 --> 00:47:52.348
And we need to take her back
into protective custody

886
00:47:52.481 --> 00:47:55.316
until we've eliminated
the threat the Fan poses.

887
00:47:55.317 --> 00:47:56.852
- Thank you.
- No problem.

888
00:47:56.952 --> 00:47:58.187
- (vehicle approaches)
- (horn honks)

889
00:47:58.287 --> 00:48:00.822
- COWORKER: See you. Laura.
- Night.

890
00:48:00.922 --> 00:48:02.858
(phone ringing)

891
00:48:02.958 --> 00:48:04.393
- (chuckles)
- (phone beeps)

892
00:48:04.493 --> 00:48:07.362
Oh. wow. Five after 10:00.

893
00:48:07.363 --> 00:48:09.531
Starting to get worried.

894
00:48:10.566 --> 00:48:13.069
Yeah. they kept me late again.

895
00:48:13.169 --> 00:48:17.239
They have me proofreading
this food allergy cookbook.

896
00:48:17.339 --> 00:48:19.674
If I have to read
one more word about aquafaba.

897
00:48:19.675 --> 00:48:21.810
I am going to hurl.

898
00:48:25.381 --> 00:48:26.515
(chuckles softly)

899
00:48:26.615 --> 00:48:28.184
I know.

900
00:48:28.284 --> 00:48:29.651
Living the dream.

901
00:48:29.751 --> 00:48:31.587
<i>♪ In my foolish lover's
game... ♪</i>

902
00:48:31.687 --> 00:48:33.289
- (lock beeps)
- (keys drop to ground)

903
00:48:34.756 --> 00:48:36.425
(laughing):
I know.

904
00:48:40.229 --> 00:48:42.798
I know. but why should I
have to do something

905
00:48:42.898 --> 00:48:46.268
that A.I. could do
in like three seconds?

906
00:48:47.403 --> 00:48:49.036
You're right.

907
00:48:49.037 --> 00:48:50.406
You're always right.

908
00:48:50.539 --> 00:48:52.474
All righty. Mom.

909
00:48:53.709 --> 00:48:55.576
I know.

910
00:48:55.577 --> 00:48:57.713
Okay. Will do.

911
00:48:58.647 --> 00:49:00.582
I love you. too.

912
00:49:01.550 --> 00:49:02.984
Good night.

913
00:49:03.085 --> 00:49:04.720
(phone beeps)

914
00:49:04.853 --> 00:49:07.423
- <i>♪ Watching in slow motion ♪</i>
- (takes deep breath)

915
00:49:07.556 --> 00:49:11.793
- <i>♪ As you turn around and say ♪</i>
- (gasping)

916
00:49:13.395 --> 00:49:15.631
(coughing. choking)

917
00:49:15.731 --> 00:49:20.469
<i>♪ Take my breath away. ♪</i>

917
00:49:21.305 --> 00:50:21.717
